Aim

To write a Python program to demonstrate dictionary operations such as accessing elements, retrieving keys, values, items, adding a new element, and removing an element.

Algorithm

Start the program.
Create a dictionary named student with the key-value pairs:
name : "Alice"
age : 20
grade : "A"
Print the complete dictionary.
Access and print the value of the key "name" using dictionary indexing.
Use the keys() method to display all keys of the dictionary.
Use the values() method to display all values of the dictionary.
Use the items() method to display all key-value pairs.
Add a new key "city" with value "New York" to the dictionary.
Print the updated dictionary.
Use the pop() method to remove the key "age" from the dictionary.
Print the dictionary after removal.
Stop the program.

EXECUTE
student = {
    "name": "Alice",
    "age": 20,
    "grade": "A"
}

print("Dictionary:", student)
print("Name:", student["name"])
print("Keys:", student.keys())
print("Values:", student.values())
print("Items:", student.items())
student["city"] = "New York"
print("After adding:", student)
student.pop("age")
print("After remove:", student)

OUTPUT
Dictionary: {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 20, 'grade': 'A'}
Name: Alice
Keys: dict_keys(['name', 'age', 'grade'])
Values: dict_values(['Alice', 20, 'A'])
Items: dict_items([('name', 'Alice'), ('age', 20), ('grade', 'A')])
After adding: {'name': 'Alice', 'age': 20, 'grade': 'A', 'city': 'New York'}
After remove: {'name': 'Alice', 'grade': 'A', 'city': 'New York'}
